so we go ahead and do this.

547
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:53,240
We fly down there,
we check into this fleabag hotel.

548
00:34:54,080 --> 00:34:56,000
Eighteen hours we wait,
no air conditioning,

549
00:34:56,080 --> 00:34:59,040
sand crabs in the bathtub,
I say, "The hell with him,"

550
00:34:59,160 --> 00:35:00,760
when we spot an envelope,

551
00:35:02,720 --> 00:35:03,880
shoved under the door.

552
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:05,320
He rarely went on vacation,
but when he did,

553
00:35:05,440 --> 00:35:06,800
he usually booked into a remote hotel

554
00:35:06,880 --> 00:35:09,279
- in the mountains of Juchitan.
- It says,

555
00:35:09,280 --> 00:35:12,000
"There's a pilot waiting
to take you to Juchitan."

556
00:35:14,240 --> 00:35:18,760
So it's 6:00 a.m.,
we're flying low over the mountains,

557
00:35:19,040 --> 00:35:20,240
and I'm nervous.

558
00:35:20,320 --> 00:35:22,040
But he's got a touch, this bush pilot.

559
00:35:22,160 --> 00:35:25,720
He brings it right down
onto a gray pebble landing strip.

560
00:35:25,800 --> 00:35:27,480
Just as it comes down,
I see out of the corner of my eye,

561
00:35:27,560 --> 00:35:30,400
there's a jeep that's coming down
from the mountains.

562
00:35:30,800 --> 00:35:32,320
Mexican military?

563
00:35:33,240 --> 00:35:34,320
No.

564
00:35:35,160 --> 00:35:36,160
It's Holmes.

565
00:35:36,200 --> 00:35:40,040
- Mr. Irving?
- Yes, that's right. Mr. Holmes?

566
00:35:40,200 --> 00:35:42,080
- Who is this?
- Dick Suskind, sir.

567
00:35:42,160 --> 00:35:44,280
So, he's a little surprised to see Dick,

568
00:35:44,360 --> 00:35:46,640
but I explained that Dick
was my researcher and friend,

569
00:35:46,720 --> 00:35:48,920
and that's why he was there
and I couldn't do without him.

570
00:35:49,040 --> 00:35:50,040
We get in the jeep,

571
00:35:50,160 --> 00:35:53,440
and he takes us on this endless ride,
up through the mountains.

572
00:35:54,080 --> 00:35:57,520
We circled around the top of this hill
and we got to the hotel,

573
00:35:57,880 --> 00:35:59,360
which was called

574
00:36:00,200 --> 00:36:01,560
Salina Cruz.

575
00:36:04,000 --> 00:36:06,200
Holmes motions for us to follow.

576
00:36:08,600 --> 00:36:10,080
It's quiet.

577
00:36:14,960 --> 00:36:17,800
There's a room
way in the back, like a hut.

578
00:36:19,360 --> 00:36:21,480
Doesn't even have
a view of the ocean.

579
00:36:25,280 --> 00:36:26,640
We can barely see.

580
00:36:28,800 --> 00:36:34,320
There's a little slip of a man on a bed,
sitting like a monk.

581
00:36:38,360 --> 00:36:39,800
Howard Hughes.

582
00:36:44,360 --> 00:36:45,840
Howard Hughes.

583
00:36:46,800 --> 00:36:48,920
Howard Hughes is sitting right there.

584
00:36:51,640 --> 00:36:53,000
My heart...

585
00:36:55,920 --> 00:37:00,360
And then he was reaching out
through the mosquito netting,

586
00:37:01,400 --> 00:37:04,000
and he offered Dick a...

587
00:37:05,320 --> 00:37:06,480
A prune.

588
00:37:06,880 --> 00:37:08,040
A prune.

589
00:37:10,600 --> 00:37:12,000
Dick takes the prune,

590
00:37:22,360 --> 00:37:23,640
eats the prune...

591
00:37:25,600 --> 00:37:26,680
Not bad.

592
00:37:28,560 --> 00:37:32,400
And he started talking about
the extraordinary value of Mexican soil,

593
00:37:32,480 --> 00:37:34,280
organic farming, organic food,
et cetera, et cetera.

594
00:37:34,400 --> 00:37:36,800
The two of them started jabbering
like old friends.

595
00:37:36,920 --> 00:37:40,840
We ended up talking a little bit about
business, then Dick and I went home.

596
00:37:43,520 --> 00:37:44,600
- I'm a little hungry.
- Let's eat.

597
00:37:46,520 --> 00:37:49,080
Ralph, will you pick
something fabulous?

598
00:37:49,920 --> 00:37:51,840
The Latour please, '61.

599
00:37:51,920 --> 00:37:54,560
- That'll get us started. Thank you.
- Oh, yes.

600
00:37:54,680 --> 00:37:56,560
And some beluga,
shall we, gentlemen?

601
00:37:56,680 --> 00:37:57,880
Sounds good.

602
00:37:59,120 --> 00:38:01,720
You know, Howard Hughes
doesn't like caviar.

603
00:38:01,800 --> 00:38:02,800
Really?

604
00:38:02,880 --> 00:38:05,800
Really. In fact, he made a special point
of saying so.

605
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:07,400
I remember that. I...

606
00:38:07,520 --> 00:38:09,120
It was such a non sequitur.
It was a strange thing.

607
00:38:09,240 --> 00:38:12,880
It was just after Clifford
finished talking about the...

608
00:38:14,440 --> 00:38:15,880
- The crash.
- That's right. The crash.

609
00:38:16,000 --> 00:38:18,520
The one in Beverly Hills.
He nearly hit the top of that house,

610
00:38:18,600 --> 00:38:21,640
parked it right on top of the house, hurt
his back, but he walked away from it.

611
00:38:21,760 --> 00:38:24,800
And he said that people
in Beverly Hills eat caviar,

612
00:38:24,920 --> 00:38:27,720
and he doesn't like it
and then he crashed his plane.

613
00:38:30,800 --> 00:38:35,000
Okay, then let's make it
two beluga appetizers, please.

614
00:38:35,080 --> 00:38:38,960
- Three maybe.
- Three, yeah. Make it three.

615
00:38:39,040 --> 00:38:41,200
- Andrea, yeah?
- Thank you. Okay. Good.

616
00:38:43,080 --> 00:38:46,280
Did you get any sense
of his business acumen?

617
00:38:47,160 --> 00:38:48,160
Go ahead.

618
00:38:48,240 --> 00:38:50,520
It's interesting. He said that...

619
00:38:51,240 --> 00:38:55,640
Very interesting. He said that people
often think of business as business,

620
00:38:55,720 --> 00:38:58,920
which of course it is, but also...
Within business, there is also pleasure.

621
00:38:59,040 --> 00:39:01,200
You know, business is pleasure.
Pleasure can be a business.

622
00:39:01,280 --> 00:39:04,600
Business has pleasure.
It's both. It's both at the same time.

623
00:39:05,080 --> 00:39:07,840
I didn't really understand it,
but after a while it sunk in,

624
00:39:07,960 --> 00:39:12,360
and I realized, you know,
that's his genius.

625
00:39:22,040 --> 00:39:24,480
This is your check for writing services.

626
00:39:24,600 --> 00:39:28,160
The second check for Mr. Hughes,
or, Octavio, sorry...

627
00:39:28,280 --> 00:39:30,960
It's gonna take
a little longer to process.

628
00:39:31,040 --> 00:39:34,200
I understand you're authorized
to receive Mr. Hughes' payment?

629
00:39:34,320 --> 00:39:37,400
Yeah, I am, I am, thank you.
But don't take too long, all right?

630
00:39:37,480 --> 00:39:40,400
Life magazine is prepared
to offer $250,000

631
00:39:40,520 --> 00:39:44,640
for worldwide exclusive rights
to serialize the Howard Hughes story.

632
00:39:47,760 --> 00:39:49,600
That's a record, Harold.

633
00:39:51,520 --> 00:39:54,960
I'm wondering if it's enough of a record,
Ralph.

634
00:39:58,880 --> 00:40:00,440
Oh, jeez.
The money makes this real.

635
00:40:01,600 --> 00:40:03,960
You can still back out,
but you gotta tell me now.

636
00:40:04,040 --> 00:40:05,040
- Back out?
- Yeah.

637
00:40:05,120 --> 00:40:07,520
Fuck, no!
We're the goddamn Musketeers.

638
00:40:07,640 --> 00:40:10,040
Good. That's good.
Don't spend any money, though.

639
00:40:10,160 --> 00:40:11,880
Better we keep it for later,
in case we need it.

640
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:13,000
Absolutely.

641
00:40:13,001 --> 00:40:14,560
In other news,
the Supreme Court has agreed to hear

642
00:40:14,680 --> 00:40:18,960
the TWA shareholders' case against
reclusive billionaire Howard Hughes.

643
00:40:19,200 --> 00:40:23,320
A loss could cost Hughes
$137,000,000

644
00:40:23,400 --> 00:40:25,480
and devastate his financial empire.

645
00:40:25,600 --> 00:40:27,320
The Nixon Justice Department
has thus far refused...

646
00:40:27,440 --> 00:40:28,560
We gotta reach big.

647
00:40:28,640 --> 00:40:31,520
We'll go for texture, gritty details,
we need blood, we need money,

648
00:40:31,640 --> 00:40:34,520
we need real juicy,
Shakespearean, big stuff...

649
00:40:34,640 --> 00:40:37,240
You want to critique a sitting president
who's also a war criminal?

650
00:40:37,320 --> 00:40:38,440
- No, no, no.
- You can do anything you want.

651
00:40:38,560 --> 00:40:40,440
You can impact culture
with something like this.

652
00:40:40,560 --> 00:40:42,480
"Impact culture." I want to make
some money and not get caught.

653
00:40:42,560 --> 00:40:44,280
You know,
we've got to make this plausible.

654
00:40:44,360 --> 00:40:46,680
Dick, I handed them
three yellow letters.

655
00:40:46,760 --> 00:40:49,640
They gave me $500,000.
Is that plausible?

656
00:40:49,760 --> 00:40:51,280
I don't think so.

657
00:40:55,240 --> 00:40:56,600
- You want to get a drink?
- Okay.

658
00:40:56,680 --> 00:40:59,040
I'm gonna change my shirt.
I'll be right out.

659
00:40:59,960 --> 00:41:03,160
- I'm heading home.
- You go. I'm sticking for a while.

660
00:41:04,160 --> 00:41:06,040
- See you, Tom.
- Good night.

661
00:41:25,240 --> 00:41:28,200
- Tommy, can I use your phone?
- Yeah, sure, go right ahead.

662
00:41:32,200 --> 00:41:34,360
I saw Elmyr a few months ago in Ibiza.

663
00:41:34,680 --> 00:41:37,080
So, how is our old friend Elmyr?

664
00:41:37,480 --> 00:41:39,280
Well, I was having dinner with friends,

665
00:41:39,360 --> 00:41:42,040
